{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d356dbaa-b000-43dc-b6b8-59e229611a94","content":"## What Changed\n\nC# 13 (carried into C# 14) introduced **implicit conversions from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`**. This changes overload resolution: `array.Contains(num)` now binds to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains(this ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)   // ← NEW winner\n```\n\ninstead of the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains(this IEnumerable<int>, int)          // ← old winner\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, which cannot be captured in expression trees. The tree either fails to compile or produces a node the interpreter cannot execute at runtime.\n\n## How to Fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `Enumerable` overload:\n\n**Option A — Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — Call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:**\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth restore the original method binding and work under `preferInterpretation: true`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a2c0dcc3-6ae5-415b-bc55-c2d48b5e64f8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension methods. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"extension everything\"), and more relevantly, the compiler changed how it resolves certain extension methods.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is specifically about `array.Contains(num)` in an expression tree context.\n\nIn .NET 9 and earlier, when you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, the compiler resolves this to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>(array, num)` — a static method call on `Enumerable`. This works fine in expression trees because it's represented as a `MethodCallExpression` calling a known static method.\n\n\nIn .NET 10, something changed with how the compiler resolves method calls on arrays — possibly new built-in methods were added to `System.Array` or the method resolution order shifted, which could be causing the expression tree to reference a method that can't be properly represented or serialized. compile time. The issue is that it compiles successfully but fails at runtime when `preferInterpretation: true` is set. I'm wondering if .NET 10 introduced changes to how `MemoryExtensions.Contains` works or if there's something about extension types in C# 14 that's affecting method resolution for arrays in expression trees.\n\nActually, I think the real culprit might be the implicit span conversions added in C# 13. If the compiler is now resolving `array.Contains(value)` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`, that would explain the runtime failure—`ReadOnlySpan<T>` can't be used in expression trees since it's a ref struct. Though that should fail at compile time during the lambda-to-expression-tree conversion, not at runtime. Unless the expression tree is being built in a way where the issue only manifests during interpretation. Reading through the user's code, I see they're building an expression tree with `array.Contains(num)`. If C# 14 resolves this to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` which requires a `ReadOnlySpan<int>`, the compiler would reject it outright since expression trees can't contain ref structs. But the user reports a runtime error, so maybe the expression tree still compiles to `Enumerable.Contains` and something about the interpreter's behavior has changed in .NET 10.\n\nC# 14's first-class span types improvements are likely the culprit here—implicit span conversions could be causing the method resolution to shift. The issue might be that the compiler allows this in expression trees somehow, but the runtime interpreter doesn't actually support it, or the user is conflating a compile-time failure with a runtime one. I'm second-guessing whether this is actually a compile-time error or a runtime issue—the compiler might reject the expression tree outright since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` can't be represented in expression trees, or there could be a subtle difference in how C# 14 handles this. The most likely scenario is that the user needs to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains` or cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>` to force the correct overload resolution and avoid the span conversion altogether. I'll focus on explaining the overload resolution change as the root cause and provide a clear fix, rather than getting caught up in whether the error happens at compile time or runtime.","outputTokens":4148,"requestId":"8853:71DA5:173EFD:1B3D22:69FA8F78"},"id":"036d2dfb-ed95-4fd0-8645-0ec1606df387","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:48:10.134Z","parentId":"fe31eaf1-9dab-401d-8a4c-20ddf6bfc12e"}
